                    "firstName": "Alex",
                    "lastName": "Fain"
                }
            ],
            "abstractNote": "Fain A. 1994. Adaptation, specificity and host-parasite coevolution in mites (Acari). Inlerniilional Journal for Parasitology 24: 1273-1283. Parasitism by mites is widespread and involves all the c1ass~s of vertebrates, from fishes to marrunals. Owing to their small size and their great plasticity, mites are able to adapt to a wide range of habitats. Most of the species ar; ectoparasites but endoparasitism, especially in the respiratory tract, is common in birds and mammals. The morphological modifications appearing during the process adaptation to parasitic life, especially in Myobiidae, are analysed. Two kinds of characters are particularly important: the constructive specialized characters, consisting of the production of new structures, especially attachment organs allowing the mite to attach to the skin and the hair of tbe host, and regressive characters. Regression of the external structures is the most important phenomenon appearing in the process of evolution of parasitic mites. The importance of the regression in the parasite is correlated with the degree of evolution of the host. Host and parasite have a parallel evolution, but they go in opposite directions. The author surmises that the regressive evolution is related to the immunological reactions of the host tbat tend to reject the parasite. To escape from this rejection the parasite tends to select the less antigenic and therefore the most regressed phenotype. Specificity is generally strict in permanent parasites. Coevolulion of host and parastie is studied.in the family Myobiidae which parasitizes marsupials, insectivores, bats and rodents. The concordance between the radiations of the mites and that of their hosts is very high.",
